# Loose Cushion Cut Diamond: Prices, Grades & the Round vs Cushion Reality

A loose cushion cut diamond starts at [$1,891 for a GIA 1ct G-VS1 Ideal Cushion Modified](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/23740863?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) in current certified market inventory — compared to $3,230 for a GIA 1ct G-VS2 Excellent round at the same retailer. That 41% price difference is not a coincidence. It's the single most important reason buyers choose cushion cut loose.

Lab-grown loose cushion cuts push the value even further: a [1.5ct IGI D-VVS2 Excellent Cushion Modified lab at $1,621](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29055737?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational), or a [2ct IGI D-VVS1 Ideal at $2,606](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28884982?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). These prices reshape what's possible.

---

**TL;DR**

- **Cushion is 35–45% cheaper than round** at the same carat/grade — the Pillow Premium works in cushion buyers' favor
- **Best natural value:** [1ct GIA G-VS1 Ideal Cushion Modified — $1,891](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/23740863?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)
- **Best lab value:** [2ct IGI D-VVS1 Ideal Cushion Modified — $2,606](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28884982?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)
- **3ct lab cushion (GIA):** [D-VVS1 Ideal — $5,962](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/26315453?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — same price as a natural 1ct round

→ **Priority rule:** Buy loose before you buy a setting. The Modified Brilliant Split — choosing between cushion modified brilliant (crushed ice) and cushion brilliant (large facets) — can only be made with stones in hand. Once set, that decision is locked in forever.

---

## Why Buy a Loose Cushion Cut Diamond?

Buying a stone loose — before choosing a setting — is how experienced diamond buyers shop. It's also how you get the best price. Pre-set rings carry a markup on the setting, a markup on the stone, and often a markup on the brand.

Buying the stone loose from a certified marketplace and then having it set locally or online separates the two costs. You control each purchase independently. You can take your time.

For cushion cuts specifically, buying loose has an extra advantage: you can evaluate the faceting pattern before committing. A cushion modified brilliant looks dramatically different from a cushion brilliant loose — one gives you a hypnotic crushed-ice sparkle, the other gives you larger, chunkier flashes of light.

That comparison is only possible stone-in-hand. Set into a ring, the difference still exists, but you're committed. This is the one decision you can't revisit after the fact.

Loose cushion diamonds are certified by GIA or IGI — you get a full grading report with cut, color, clarity, carat weight, fluorescence, and measurements. The certificate travels with the stone and stays valid permanently. When you buy a pre-set ring, the stone's individual certificate is often absorbed into the overall ring documentation, making individual verification harder.

---

## The Modified Brilliant Split

The cushion cut comes in two fundamentally different faceting styles, and they do not look the same.

**Cushion Modified Brilliant** — also called "crushed ice" or "pillow" — has a complex arrangement of small facets that creates a scintillating, multi-point sparkle pattern. Looking into a cushion modified brilliant loose, you see dozens of tiny flashes rather than a few large ones. It reads as bright, hypnotic, and modern. Almost all loose GIA cushion diamonds in the market today are cushion modified brilliants.

**Cushion Brilliant** — sometimes called "old mine style" — has larger, chunkier facets arranged more like an antique old mine cut. The sparkle pattern is bigger and bolder: fewer flashes, each one larger. This is the look of vintage cushion cuts and creates a distinctly different aesthetic from the crushed ice style.

The Modified Brilliant Split is the decision point that separates cushion buyers who are happy with their purchase from those who aren't. Both styles look beautiful in photos. Side by side, loose, the difference is immediately apparent.

Once set in a ring and photographed for Instagram, they can appear almost identical. The time to choose is before the stone is set.

Most buyers default to cushion modified brilliant without realizing the alternative exists. If you want the vintage, high-contrast sparkle of a cushion brilliant, search specifically for that cut style. If you're happy with the modern crushed-ice look, cushion modified is widely available and well-priced.

Ask for an HD video of any loose cushion diamond before purchasing — the video will show the sparkle pattern more accurately than any photo.

