## Loose Cushion Cut Diamond Price by Color Grade

Color matters differently in cushion cuts than in rounds. The cushion's larger facets can hold warmth more visibly than a round's precise faceting — but this cuts both ways.

G color reads as white in a cushion, just as it does in a round. H and I color may show warmth in white gold settings, especially in stones above 2ct.

| Color Grade | 1ct Price Range | Best Pick |
|---|---|---|
| D | [$4,410–$4,921](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/12473312?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | Investment / collector only |
| E–F | [$2,064–$2,265](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/25944037?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | Colorless appearance, best value |
| G | [$1,891–$2,252](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/23740863?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | Sweet spot — face-up white, max value |
| H–I | Below market data threshold | Yellow gold only; avoid platinum/white gold |

G is where I stop for almost all cushion buyers. F adds $150–$200 for no visible color improvement. D adds over $2,000 for the same.

---

## Loose Cushion Cut Diamond Price by Clarity Grade

At 1ct, cushion modified brilliants are reliably eye-clean at VS2. The crushed-ice faceting of the cushion modified style is actually better at hiding inclusions than round brilliant — all those tiny facets scatter light over inclusions rather than directing light toward them.

This means cushion buyers can sometimes go lower on clarity than round buyers and maintain the same eye-clean standard.

- **VVS1–VVS2:** Certificate prestige only. No visible advantage over VS2 at any cushion size.
- **VS1–VS2:** Eye-clean in all conditions. My recommended floor for cushion cut loose stones.
- **SI1:** Often eye-clean in cushion modified brilliant. Request video before buying — the crushed ice faceting hides SI1 inclusions better than most cuts. Potentially saves $300–$600 at 1ct.
- **SI2:** Occasional eye-clean stones exist. High risk at 2ct+. Not recommended without expert review.

---

## The Pillow Premium

Here's the comparison that matters most for cushion buyers:

| Stone | Carat | Color-Clarity | Price |
|---|---|---|---|
| GIA Round Brilliant Excellent | 1ct | G-VS2 | [$3,230](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29090690?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) |
| GIA Cushion Modified Ideal | 1ct | G-VS1 | [$1,891](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/23740863?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) |
| **Savings** | — | — | **$1,339 (41%)** |

The Pillow Premium is the budget advantage cushion buyers capture over round buyers. At the same quality level, a loose cushion costs 35–45% less than a round brilliant. That gap is consistent across all carat weights.

What this means in practice: a buyer with a $3,230 budget can get a 1ct round G-VS2 — or a 1ct cushion G-VS1 for $1,891 and put the remaining $1,339 toward a platinum setting. Or they can use that $3,230 to buy a 1.5ct cushion instead of a 1ct round.

The Pillow Premium is not about cushion being inferior. Cushion cut's lower price relative to round reflects lower demand in the market, not lower quality. For buyers who prefer the cushion shape, this is a straight value advantage.

---

