## GIA vs IGI for Loose Cushion Cut Diamonds

When buying loose, the certification choice matters. Both GIA and IGI issue full grading reports for cushion cut diamonds — but their standards differ.

**GIA** is the stricter lab. GIA's color and clarity grades tend to be more conservative — a stone that GIA grades G-VS1 might get an F-VVS2 from IGI. This means GIA-certified cushion loose diamonds carry a premium (5–15%) over comparable IGI stones.

**IGI** is the standard for lab-grown diamonds. IGI-certified lab cushions are widely accepted and priced competitively. For natural cushion diamonds, IGI is less common but exists (one 3.09ct IGI cushion appears in our 3ct data above at $36,725).

For natural cushion loose diamonds: buy GIA. For lab-grown cushion loose diamonds: IGI Ideal is the best combination of value and verification.

---

## Loose Cushion Cut Diamond vs Pre-Set Ring

The question buyers ask most: should I buy a loose stone or a pre-set ring?

Buy loose if:
- You want to choose the exact stone (color, clarity, faceting pattern)
- You have a specific setting in mind that isn't available pre-set
- Budget is a priority — loose + local setting often beats pre-set price
- You want full certification documentation for the stone alone

Buy pre-set if:
- You want the entire ring designed and ready to ship
- You don't want to manage two separate purchases
- The setting design is unusual and difficult to source separately

The price math almost always favors buying loose. A pre-set ring markup can run 20–40% above buying stone and setting separately. At $13,679 for a 2ct cushion modified, saving 20–40% on the setting component adds up fast.

---

## Elongated Loose Cushion Cut Diamond

The elongated cushion cut — length-to-width ratio of 1.15–1.30 — is a distinct aesthetic category in the loose market. It looks visually different from a square cushion: more like an elongated oval with cushion faceting, and it makes fingers look longer.

Elongated cushion cuts are less common loose than square cushions, which means inventory is thinner and you may need to search more specifically. Look for L/W ratios above 1.15 in the stone's GIA measurements — the certificate lists exact dimensions in millimeters. A 1ct elongated cushion that measures 6.5mm × 5.5mm reads very differently face-up from a 1ct square cushion at 5.8mm × 5.5mm.

See our complete [elongated cushion cut diamond guide](/elongated-cushion-cut-diamond) for full L/W ratio guidance and specific picks.

---

## Fancy Color Loose Cushion Cut Diamonds

The loose cushion market extends beyond white diamonds into yellow and pink — and the price structure is completely different.

**Loose Yellow Cushion Cut Diamond:** Natural fancy yellow cushion cuts start from around [$1,549 per carat](/yellow-cushion-cut-diamond) for Fancy Yellow grades, with Fancy Intense and Fancy Vivid prices escalating sharply. Lab-grown yellow cushion cuts are available for a fraction of the natural price. See the full price breakdown in our [yellow cushion cut diamond guide](/yellow-cushion-cut-diamond).

**Loose Pink Cushion Cut Diamond:** Natural fancy pink cushion cuts start at [$9,488 for a 1ct Fancy Brownish Pink](/pink-cushion-cut-diamond) and reach nearly $1M for Fancy Intense Purplish Pink at 1ct. Lab-grown pink cushion cuts start from [$3,045 for 5ct IGI Fancy Vivid Pink](/pink-cushion-cut-diamond) — extraordinary value for color intensity that doesn't exist in nature at any retail price. See our [pink cushion cut diamond guide](/pink-cushion-cut-diamond) for full pricing.

For loose fancy color cushion cuts, buying loose matters even more than for white diamonds — color saturation varies significantly between individual stones at the same GIA grade, and only a video review or in-person viewing reveals the actual face-up color.

---

## What to Look for When Buying a Loose Cushion Cut Diamond

Most buyers focus on the 4Cs and stop there. For cushion cut loose diamonds, there are four extra factors that matter — and none of them appear on the certificate.

**Length-to-width ratio.** The GIA report lists the stone's measurements in millimeters. Divide the longer measurement by the shorter one — that's your L/W ratio. A ratio of 1.00–1.05 gives a square appearance. 1.10–1.20 gives a slightly elongated look. 1.20+ is the elongated cushion territory. Know your target ratio before searching.

**Faceting pattern.** The certificate won't tell you if a stone is "crushed ice" or "chunky facet" cushion modified. Only video shows this. Always watch the HD video before buying any loose cushion. Still images lie.

**Table percentage.** Cushion modified brilliants with tables between 55–65% give the best light performance. Very high tables (above 70%) spread the stone but can reduce depth and brilliance. This detail is sometimes listed in the stone's lab report; if not, ask the vendor.

**Fluorescence.** Cushion cuts with strong blue fluorescence can look hazy under UV-heavy lighting (outdoors on a bright day). In most indoor lighting it's fine or even beneficial — fluorescence makes a G-H color stone look a shade whiter. For loose cushion diamonds, I generally recommend none-to-faint fluorescence for maximum versatility, but medium-blue on G-H color is acceptable if the video looks clean.

**Vendor return policy.** Any reputable loose diamond vendor offers 30 days return minimum. If the return window is under 30 days, or if loose stones are final sale, walk away. The only way to verify a loose cushion's true appearance is in the setting, under natural light. Returns protect you.

---

## How to Set a Loose Cushion Cut Diamond

You have three main options after buying a loose stone.

**Local jeweler:** Bring the certified loose stone to a jeweler near you. Get a quote for the setting you want. Many local jewelers have setting catalogs from manufacturers — you're not limited to what's in their display case. This is often the most affordable route, and you can inspect the quality of the setting work in person before paying.

**Online setting vendors:** Sites that sell loose stones also sell compatible settings. The stone ships to them, they set it, and the finished ring ships to you. This works well when you buy the stone and setting from the same vendor — no transfer coordination needed. For cushion cuts, confirm the setting's cushion size compatibility before ordering.

**Custom jeweler:** If you have a very specific design in mind, a custom jeweler can build the setting around your exact stone dimensions. This is the most expensive route but gives you complete design control. Expect 3–6 weeks turnaround and provide the GIA report with stone measurements to the jeweler at the start.

For cushion cuts, prong count matters. Four-prong settings show more of the stone's face-up surface. Six-prong settings hold the stone more securely — important for stones above 2ct.

A halo setting adds apparent size but changes the visual weight of the piece significantly. Solitaire settings let the cushion's faceting pattern speak for itself. Pavé bands add sparkle without altering the center stone's appearance.

If you're not sure which setting direction to go, buy the stone first. Loose diamonds can sit in a temporary holder while you decide. The setting decision is reversible — the stone decision is where your real money goes.

Most buyers spend too long choosing the setting and not long enough evaluating the stone itself.

---

## Cushion Modified Brilliant vs Standard Cushion — Which to Buy?

Most buyers won't find "standard cushion brilliant" in mainstream certified inventory — the market has shifted heavily toward cushion modified. But if you're shopping across multiple retailers, you may encounter both.

For engagement ring buyers who want:
- **Maximum sparkle and brightness:** Cushion modified brilliant. The crushed-ice pattern maximizes light return.
- **Vintage aesthetic, bold flashes:** Cushion brilliant (old mine style). Fewer, larger light returns.
- **Photography-friendly:** Cushion modified. It photographs brighter.
- **In-person impact:** Both are striking, but cushion brilliant has a more dramatic real-world presence under a single light source.

Neither is objectively better. Choose based on the look you want — and make that choice loose, with a video, before committing.

